FB98\"|Winner\n| 5.\n| [[2016 World Seniors Championship|2016]]\n| [[World Seniors Championship]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} {{sortname|Darren|Morgan}}\n| 2\u20131\n|}\n\n=== Variant events finals: 3 (3 titles) ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n|width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n|width=\"200\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| [[2009 Six-red World Championship|2009]]\n| [[Six-red World Championship]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} {{sortname|Mark|Williams|Mark Williams (snooker player)}}\n| align=\"centr\"|6\u20133\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 2.\n| [[2012 Six-red World Championship|2012]]\n| [[Six-red World Championship]] <small>(2)</small>\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Shaun|Murphy|Shaun Murphy (snooker player)}}\n| align=\"centr\"|8\u20134\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 3.\n| [[2013 Six-red World Championship|2013]]\n| [[Six-red World Championship]] <small>(3)</small>\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} {{sortname|Neil|Robertson|Neil Robertson (snooker player)}}\n| align=\"centr\"|8\u20134\n|}\n\n===Pro\u2013am finals: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n|width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n|width=\"200\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| 2007\n| German Open\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]]\n| 4\u20133<ref name=GSC>{{cite web|title=2007 German Open|url=http://globalsnookercentre.co.uk:80/files/Results/2007-8/07-8-International/2007-Elchingen-Open.htm|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314082331/http://globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/Results/2007-8/07-8-International/2007-Elchingen-Open.htm|archivedate=14 March 2008|access-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Maximum breaks==\n{{See also|Maximum break}}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"20\"|'''{{Abbr|No.|Number}}'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n!width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n!width=\"200\"|'''Opponent'''\n!width=\"30\"|'''Ref.'''\n|-\n| 1.\n| [[2017 Championship League|2017]]\n| [[Championship League]]\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} {{sortname|Neil|Robertson|dab=snooker player}}\n| <ref name=\"Maximum break\">{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=541|title=Championship League - Winners' Group|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2.\n| [[2017 Championship League|2017]]\n| [[Championship League]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} {{sortname|John|Higgins|dab=snooker player}}\n| <ref name=\"Maximum break\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Mark Davis}}\n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/mark-davis/ Mark Davis] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n*\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Mark}}\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hastings]]\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:World champions in snooker]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Mark Davis}}\n{{short description|English professional snooker player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Mark Davis\n| image         = Mark Davis PHC 2016-3.jpg\n| caption       = Paul Hunter Classic 2016\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1972|8|12}}\n| birth_place   = [[St Leonards-on-Sea|St. Leonards]], [[England]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname      = The Battler from Hastings\n| Professional  = 1991\u2013\n| High ranking  = 12 {{small|(June 2013 and March\u2013May 2014)}}\n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,355,440\n| High break    = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''' {{small|(2 times)}} \n| Century break = 256\n| Best finish   = ''Runner-up'' {{small|([[2018 English Open (snooker)|2018 English Open]])}} \n| Ranking wins  =\n| Other wins    = 5\n| World champ   =\n}}\n\n'''Mark Davis''' (born 12 August 1972) is an English professional [[snooker]] player from [[St Leonards-on-Sea|St. Leonards]] in Sussex, England. Davis became professional in 1991 but for many years was considered something of a journeyman; however, he vastly improved his game in the late 2000s, and as a result managed to get in the top 16 for the first time in 2012. The highlights of his career so far have been winning the [[Masters Qualifying Event|Benson & Hedges Championship]] in 2002 (earning him an appearance at the [[Masters (snooker)|Masters]]), and the [[six-red snooker]] world championships three times (in [[2009 Six-red World Championship|2009]], [[2012 Six-red World Championship|2012]] and [[2013 Six-red World Championship|2013]]). Davis reached his first ranking event final in 2018, where he lost to [[Stuart Bingham]] in the final of the [[2018 English Open (snooker)|English Open]]. Prior to this he was widely considered to be the best player never to have reached a ranking final.\n\nDavis is the oldest snooker player to make an official [[maximum break]] of 147 points in a professional competition, at the age of 44 years and 202 days. He broke his own previous record of 44 years and 151 days, making his second maximum break 51 days after his first.\n\n== Career ==\nDavis made his debut in the main draw of the [[World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] in [[1994 World Snooker Championship|1994]], losing in the first round to [[Terry Griffiths]]. The [[1995 World Snooker Championship|following year]] he won his first match at the Crucible, beating [[Ken Doherty]] in the first round, before being knocked out by [[Peter Ebdon]] in the second round. Davis came close to losing his Main Tour status in the late 1990s, but recovered in the early 2000s to return to the top 48. Reaching the quarter-finals of the 2001 [[Regal Scottish]] tournament, his second career quarter-final, was the main catalyst for this. His success in reaching the 2008 World Championship came after 2 poor seasons, leaving him at No. 58 in the rankings. He opened the 2008/2009 season strongly by qualifying for the [[2008 Northern Ireland Trophy|Northern Ireland Trophy]] and defeating local hope [[Joe Swail]] 5\u20134 in the first round, before beating [[Ding Junhui]] 5\u20134 in the last 32 in one of the best wins of his career.  He was beaten in the last 16 5\u20132 by [[Ali Carter]]. He followed this up by also qualifying for the [[2008 Bahrain Championship|Bahrain]] and [[2008 UK Championship (snooker)|UK]] Championships, though he was forced to pull out early in his last-32 match against [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]] in the latter, due to a stomach upset.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/7781545.stm | title=O'Sullivan survives McLeod charge | date=13 December 2008 | publisher=BBC | accessdate=15 November 2018 }}</ref> He exceeded his 2007/2008 ranking points total after only five of the eight events of the 2008/2009 season.\nIn 2009 Davis won the [[2009 Six-red World Championship|Six-Red World Championship]].\nIn 2010, Davis reached the second round of the [[2010 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the first time in 15 years by defeating sixth seed [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]].\n\nDavis has compiled over 200 competitive centuries in his career up to October 2016, putting him 27th in the top of the players reaching a century of centuries in a career.\n\nHe got his career best tournament break of 143 in the [[2010 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] on 29 March 2010, the 93rd century of his career, in a wild-card round match against [[Tian Pengfei]].\nAfter an excellent 2009/2010 season, he reached the top 32 of the players and also claim his highest rank, by being ranked 26th.\n\nHe also qualified for the 2010 Shanghai Masters event where he reached the last-eight beating [[Marco Fu]] and [[Stephen Maguire]] on the way before surrendering a 4\u20131 lead against [[Jamie Burnett]] and going out 5\u20134. However, his strong performances continued and took him to a career high ranking of 18.\n\n===2011/2012 season===\nDavis qualified for all but two of the ranking events in the [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/2012 season]].<ref name=\"2011/12\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=15&season=2011 | title=Mark Davis 2011/2012 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> He could only advance beyond the first round in the [[2011 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], where he lost 3\u20135 to [[Mark Selby]] in the last 16.<ref name=\"2011/12\"/> Davis played in all 12 of the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012|Players Tour Championship]] events during the season, reaching the final of [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 4|Event 4]], where he lost to Selby 0\u20134. This result was a large contributory factor to Davis finishing 16th on the PTC [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]], inside the top 24 who made the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011|title=Order of Merit|publisher=Snooker.org |date=8 January 2012|accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> At the Finals he beat [[Tom Ford]], before losing to [[Stephen Maguire]] in the last 16.<ref name=\"2011/12\"/> Davis' season came to an end when he suffered a heavy 2\u201310 loss, while feeling unwell, in the [[2012 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] to [[Ali Carter]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2135595/Snooker-World-Championship-2012-Ali-Carter-eases-past-Mark-Davis.html | title=Carter cruises into round two as Davis suffers at The Crucible | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | date=26 April 2012 | accessdate=20 May 2012 | location=London}}</ref> He finished the season ranked world number 19, with the elite top 16 places still eluding him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616125200/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0%2C%2C13165~176157%2C00.pdf |archivedate=16 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2012/2013 season===\nDavis started the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/2013 season]] very successfully by reaching the first ranking event semi-final of his 21-year professional career at the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]].<ref name=\"SF\">{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2827261,00.html | title=In Form Bingham Keeps Run Going | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> His run included wins over local favourite [[Ding Junhui]], [[Jamie Burnett]] and [[Graeme Dott]] to set up a last 4 clash with [[Stuart Bingham]] who had won the previous week's [[Asian Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 1|Asian PTC]].<ref name=\"SF\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2204168,00.html |title=Wuxi Classic 2012 results |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=24 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729082331/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2204168%2C00.html |archivedate=29 July 2014 }}</ref> He trailed 0\u20134 at the mid-session interval, before coming back to play inspired snooker to lead 5\u20134 in the best of 11 frames match. However, Bingham then levelled the contest before compiling a 134 break to win the decider and end Davis' hopes of a first ranking final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2827997,00.html | title=Closing Century Puts Bingham into Final | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> At the [[2012 Six-red World Championship|Six-red World Championship]] he claimed the title by defeating [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] 8\u20134 in the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=179 | title=SangSom 6 Red World Championship (2012) | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> The winner's cheque of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]40,000 is the biggest of his career to date.<ref name=\"2012 6R\">{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2835088,00.html | title=Six of the Best For Davis | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> In the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]] Davis saw off [[Jack Lisowski]] (5\u20132), home favourite [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] (5\u20131) and [[Martin Gould]] (5\u20132), to reach his second successive ranking semi-final.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=15&season=2012 | title=Mark Davis 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> There he played close friend [[Barry Hawkins]] and was beaten 4\u20136.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/ebdon-cruises-goldfields-open-final-062115157.html | title=Ebdon to face Hawkins in Goldfields final | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2012 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] he beat [[Cao Yupeng]] 6\u20131 in the first round and led three-time champion [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] 5\u20132 in the second round, before withstanding a fightback from Higgins which included a [[Maximum break|147]], to win a decider.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20607987 | title=UK Snooker Championship 2012: Higgins out despite 147 | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> Davis saw off [[Matthew Stevens]] 6\u20134 in the quarter-finals, however his lack of experience on the big stage showed in his semi-final against [[Mark Selby]], as he was beaten 4\u20139.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20652501 | title=UK Snooker Championship 2012: Mark Selby beats Mark Davis | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref>\nDavis qualified for the [[2013 Masters (snooker)|2013 Masters]] tournament thanks to his form earning him a place in the top 16. At his first outing in the tournament for 13 years he faced world number nine [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] in the first round and lost 2\u20136.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2261932/Snooker-Mark-Allen-beats-Mark-Davis-Masters.html | title=Allen sees off Davis to book place in last eight of Masters | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=1 April 2013 | location=London | first=Nick | last=Metcalfe | date=13 January 2013}}</ref> This began a dip in form for Davis as he lost in the qualifying round of the [[2013 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], the first round of both the [[2013 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] and [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Finals|Players Tour Championship Finals]] and in the second round of the [[2013 China Open (snooker)|China Open]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> However, he was still ranked 16 in the world at the cut-off for the [[2013 World Snooker Championship|2013 World Championship]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Official world rankings issued after the China Open 2013 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/b3/bb/0,,13165~179123,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=2 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FZjO85uI?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/b3/bb/0,,13165~179123,00.pdf |archivedate=2 April 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but was forced to qualify due to world number 28 and reigning champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] deciding to defend his title after taking a year away from professional snooker.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21575730 | title=Ronnie O'Sullivan to defend snooker world title | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=225 | title=Betfair World Championship Qualifiers | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> O'Sullivan was therefore the number one seed, meaning Davis dropped out of the top 16 who were guaranteed a spot in the event.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/snooker-osullivan-set-another-crucible-battle-carter-143448902.html | title=Snooker \u2013 O'Sullivan set for another Crucible battle with Carter | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=1 April 2013}}</ref> Davis beat [[Liang Wenbo]] 10\u20136 in qualifying.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He faced four-time champion [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] in the first round and claimed the best win of his career by winning 10\u20136 and played [[Stuart Bingham]] in the last 16.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22257516 | title=World Snooker Championship 2013: Mark Davis delighted at win | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> The match proved to be very tight, but from 10\u201310 Bingham pulled away to win 13\u201310 with Davis saying afterwards that he had done well to win 10 frames such was his disappointment at the way he had performed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3161660,00.html | title=Bingham Reaches First Crucible Quarter | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref> However, he finished the season inside the top 16 for the very first time, at world number 13.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp | title=Ranking History | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014 season===\nDavis reached the quarter-finals of the [[2013 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]] but lost 5\u20133 to [[Mark Selby]].<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web|title=Mark Davis 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2013&player=15|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>\nAt the [[2013 Six-red World Championship]] he defended his title by defeating [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] 8\u20134 in the final.<ref name=\"6-red 2013\">{{cite web|title=SangSom 6 Red World Championship (2013)|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=270|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> Only a week later he won his next tournament, the [[2013 General Cup|General Cup]] in Hong Kong, beating Robertson again in the final, this time by 7\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|title=General Cup (2013)|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=313|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> A second ranking event quarter-final of the year came at the [[2013 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] with comfortable 5\u20132 and 5\u20131 victories over [[Ali Carter]] and [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]]. However, he then squandered a 4\u20132 lead over [[Xiao Guodong]] to be beaten 5\u20134.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bexhillobserver.net/sport/other-sports/breaking-news-davis-beaten-in-decider-1-5511882 | title=Breaking news: Davis beaten in decider | publisher=Bexhill-on-Sea Observer | accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> At the [[2014 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] he forced a decider in the first round against [[Mark Selby]], having been 4\u20130 down but lost the 55-minute final frame to be defeated 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/25705472 | title=Masters 2014: Mark Selby and John Higgins into quarter-finals | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> In the quarter-finals of the [[2014 German Masters|German Masters]], Davis lost in an extremely close match with [[Rod Lawler]] 5\u20134.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/trump-charges-into-german-masters-semis_sto4117448/story.shtml | title=Trump charges into German Masters semis | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> Davis was an automatic qualifier for the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the first time in his career this season and said before the event that his minimum goal was to win through to the quarter-finals, but he was beaten 10\u20135 in the first round by [[Dominic Dale]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hastingsobserver.co.uk/sport/other-sports/davis-keen-to-make-his-mark-1-6015326 | title=Davis keen to make his mark | publisher=[[Hastings & St. Leonards Observer]] | accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/9281311/world-championship-dominic-dale-rolls-into-round-two-mark-selby-leads-ali-carter | title=World Championship: Dominic Dale and Neil Robertson reach second round at Crucible | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> Davis hung on to his top 16 ranking at the end of the season as he was the world number 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0,,13165~180593,00.pdf |title=World Snooker Rankings After the 2014 World Championship |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508030740/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0%2C%2C13165~180593%2C00.pdf |archivedate=8 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===2014/2015 season===\n[[File:Mark Davis at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2015-02-05 03.jpg|thumb|Mark Davis at the [[2015 German Masters]]]]\nDavis began his season at the [[2014 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], with his quarter-final match against [[Stuart Bingham]] containing ten breaks above 50 in the nine frames played, which Davis edged 5\u20134.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3957612,00.html | title=Robertson To Face Davis in Bendigo | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> In Davis' fourth ranking event semi-final he lost 6\u20132 to home favourite [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3963510,00.html | title=Trump To Face Robertson in Bendigo Final | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> His second quarter-final in a ranking event of the year came at the [[2014 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], but he was defeated 6\u20131 by [[Judd Trump]]. He followed that up with a semi-final showing at the minor-ranking [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 5|Lisbon Open]] where he was whitewashed 4\u20130 by [[Stephen Maguire]].<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web|title=Mark Davis 2014/2015|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=15|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> Davis was beaten 3\u20132 by [[Stuart Bingham]] in the final of the non-ranking [[2015 Championship League|Championship League]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/bingham-is-championship-league-king/ | title=Bingham Is Championship League King | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nDavis' consistent season continued as he restricted [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] to just 38 points to thrash him 4\u20130 in reaching the last eight of the [[2015 Indian Open|Indian Open]], but he lost 4\u20132 against [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/other-sports/john-higgins-beaten-4-0-by-mark-davis-in-india.120650283 | title=John Higgins beaten 4\u20130 by Mark Davis in India | newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] | accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> Davis progressed through to his fourth ranking quarter-final of the season, the most in a single season of his career, at the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015 \u2013 Finals|PTC Grand Final]] by eliminating [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hastingsobserver.co.uk/sport/other-sports/breaking-news-davis-defeats-robertson-again-1-6656759 | title=Davis defeats Robertson again | publisher=Hasting & St. Leonards Observer | accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> He was unable to play in the semi-finals however, as Bingham knocked him out 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hastingsobserver.co.uk/sport/other-sports/davis-suffers-another-last-eight-exit-1-6659273 | title=Davis suffers another last eight exit | publisher=Hasting & St. Leonards Observer | accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> Davis earned a 4\u20130 early advantage over [[Ding Junhui]] at the [[2015 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] and won the first session 5\u20133. However, he went on to be beaten 10\u20137.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/32394837 | title=World Snooker Championship: Ding Junhui beats Mark Davis | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016 season===\nDavis' first quarter-final of the [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/2016 season]] came at the [[2015 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], courtesy of 5\u20131 and 5\u20133 wins over [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]] and [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]], but he was beaten 5\u20131 by [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]]. He lost in the third round of the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] 6\u20134 to [[Stephen Maguire]].<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=15 | title=Mark Davis 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref> Davis claimed the [[2016 World Seniors Championship|World Seniors Championship]], his first televised title in the UK, by seeing off [[Darren Morgan]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/senior-success-for-davis/ | title=Senior Success for Davis | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[2016 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the first time since 2011 after losing 10\u20135 to [[Zhang Anda]].<ref name=\"2015/16\"/>\n\n===2016/2017 season===\n[[File:Mark Davis PHC 2016-4.jpg|thumb|2016 Paul Hunter Classic]]\nDavis lost 4\u20131 to [[Mark Selby]] in the quarter-finals of the [[2016 Paul Hunter Classic|Paul Hunter Classic]]. At the [[2016 European Masters|European Masters]] he beat [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] 4\u20131 and [[Liang Wenbo]] 4\u20133 to reach another quarter-final and was defeated 4\u20131 by [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]. His third quarter-final of the year came at the [[2016 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] after he squeezed past [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 4\u20133, but he was heavily beaten 5\u20131 by [[Marco Fu]].<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=15&season=2016|title=Mark Davis 2016/2017|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Davis knocked out [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 4\u20133 in the second round of the [[2017 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] after being 3\u20130 down and then made the event's high break of 144 as he eliminated [[Fergal O'Brien]] 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/wales/38986026|title=Welsh Open 2017: Ronnie O'Sullivan knocked out by Mark Davis in second round|work=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Davis lost 4\u20133 to [[Scott Donaldson]] in the fourth round. He could not reach the [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the second year in a row after being defeated 10\u20137 in the qualifiers by [[Yan Bingtao]].<ref name=\"2016/17\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDavis lives with his wife Claire, their son Jack and their daughter Millie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onqpromotions.co.uk/mark-davis|title=Mark Davies|publisher=onqpromotions.co.uk|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Performance and rankings timeline ==\n<div style=\"width:auto; overflow:scroll\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0 0; border:1px #aaa solid; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:85%\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Tournament\n! [[Snooker season 1991/1992|1991/<br/>92]]\n! [[Snooker season 1992/1993|1992/<br/>93]]\n! [[Snooker season 1993/1994|1993/<br/>94]]\n! [[Snooker season 1994/1995|1994/<br/>95]]\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/<br/>06]]\n! [[Snooker season 2006/2007|2006/<br/>07]]\n! [[Snooker season 2007/2008|2007/<br/>08]]\n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br/>09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/<br/>10]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br/>11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br/>12]]\n! [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/<br/>13]]\n! [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/<br/>14]]\n! [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/<br/>15]]\n! [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[Snooker season